item.title: WA parliament passes unpaid fines reforms
item.description: Legislation to overhaul Western Australia's much-criticised unpaid fines regime has passed state parliament, which advocates say will reduce the number of Aboriginal people in prison.

item.title: Inquiry launched into NT federal seats
item.description: A review has been launched into a bill which would protect the Northern Territory from losing one of its two federal seats.

item.title: BHP hires finance chief Lamont from CSL
item.description: BHP has hired biotech CSL's finance boss, David Lamont, who will return to the mining giant.

item.title: Vic Ombudsman eyes ALP branch stacking
item.description: Victoria's ombudsman has been asked to investigate Labor's industrial-scale branch stacking scandal, which has thrown the state's party into turmoil.

item.title: Qld LNP plan to drug test some parents
item.description: Queensland parents who test positive to some drugs will go into mandatory rehabilitation under a Liberal National Party plan, but it's unclear if they will permanently lose their kids if they test positive a second time.

item.title: Vic duo buzz off with stolen sex toys
item.description: A sex shop has had more than $1200 worth of stock stolen in Melbourne.

item.title: Government senator wants tariffs on China
item.description: A Morrison government senator has called for Australia to slap tariffs on Chinese imports and consider seizing state-owned assets in retaliation for coronavirus.

item.title: Record virus spike in six US states
item.description: New coronavirus infections have hit record highs in six US states, marking a rising tide of cases for a second consecutive week as most states moved forward with reopening their economies.

item.title: Electric company guilty of US fire deaths
item.description: The Pacific Gas & Electric company has pleaded guilty to killing 84 people in Paradise, California after its failing electric grid caused a 2018 fire that ravaged the northern California town.

item.title: Facebook removes right-wing accounts
item.description: Facebook has removed almost 900 accounts associated with the far-right Proud Boys and American Guard, including those of supporters who marched into a protest zone in Seattle and confronted anti-racist demonstrators.
